---
import Base from "../../../layouts/Base.astro";
import PageTitle from "../../../components/PageTitle.astro";
import CTA from "../../../components/CTA.astro";

const locale = "en";
const title = "Choose your email provider";
const intro = "Catena does not host email; it integrates with a provider you choose and keeps the mailboxes in your name. Six privacy-focused, full-featured providers cover every situation we typically see; here is how to compare them.";
---
<Base
  locale={locale}
  title={title}
  description="Compare the six recommended email providers (Migadu, Mailbox.org, Hostpoint, Infomaniak, OVH Pro Mail, Mailfence): jurisdiction, pricing, language support, and how they fit the Catena Suite."
>
  <PageTitle title={title} intro={intro} />

  <article class="guide">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>What all six share</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>App-passwords.</strong> One credential per app, revocable individually, so a lost phone does not require rotating the main password.</li>
        <li><strong>Data portability.</strong> Standard IMAP / SMTP / CalDAV / CardDAV — connect any client you want (Gmail, Outlook / Microsoft 365, Apple Mail, Thunderbird, mobile) and move out to any other provider that speaks the same protocols, with standard tools.</li>
        <li><strong>Personal-mailbox archive into Nextcloud.</strong> Each user's mail (and calendars and contacts) can be archived inside their Nextcloud Files, where it joins the suite's restic + WORM backup pipeline.</li>
        <li><strong>No single sign-on from Keycloak.</strong> None of the six exposes a production-ready external IdP for end-user mailbox login. Your team keeps one extra password alongside their Keycloak password. We enforce MFA on the provider account and use app-passwords for clients, which closes the practical risk.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        The table below covers what actually differs between them:
        where they are, what they cost, what UI languages they speak,
        how they handle shared mailboxes, and whether they have a
        provisioning API.
      </p>

      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th></th>
              <th>Migadu</th>
              <th>Mailbox.org</th>
              <th>Hostpoint</th>
              <th>Infomaniak</th>
              <th>OVH Pro Mail</th>
              <th>Mailfence</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">Jurisdiction (HQ + DC)</th>
              <td>Switzerland</td>
              <td>Germany</td>
              <td>Switzerland</td>
              <td>Switzerland</td>
              <td>France + Canada region</td>
              <td>Belgium</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">Pricing (CAD, approx.) <sup>*</sup></th>
              <td>$12-40 / month per domain (unlimited mailboxes within a soft sending cap)</td>
              <td>$40 base + $1.60 / user / month</td>
              <td>$5.25 / user / month</td>
              <td>$2.50 / user / month (free tier exists)</td>
              <td>$7 / user / month</td>
              <td>$5.60 / user / month</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">French UI</th>
              <td>limited (admin English; webmail partial)</td>
              <td>none (German + English)</td>
              <td>strong</td>
              <td>strong</td>
              <td>strong</td>
              <td>strong</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">English UI</th>
              <td>strong</td>
              <td>strong</td>
              <td>strong</td>
              <td>strong</td>
              <td>partial</td>
              <td>strong</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">Shared mailbox model</th>
              <td>dedicated + alias</td>
              <td>team mailbox + Unified Mail</td>
              <td>dedicated + alias</td>
              <td>dedicated + per-user web invite</td>
              <td>dedicated + alias (true shared via Hosted Exchange)</td>
              <td>dedicated + alias + Group feature</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">Provisioning API</th>
              <td>yes</td>
              <td>partial</td>
              <td>partial</td>
              <td>yes</td>
              <td>yes (OVH API)</td>
              <td>partial</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p class="muted">
        <sup>*</sup> Prices in CAD, approximate at 2026-05-11. Provider
        pricing changes frequently; we pull live numbers the day we
        quote.
      </p>

      <p>
        The "provisioning API" column matters when your team turns
        over often: a real API lets the install / portal create and
        retire mailboxes without you logging into the provider's
        admin panel. Providers marked "partial" require some manual
        steps; providers marked "no" require you to use the web
        admin every time.
      </p>

      <h2>What "shared mailboxes" means in practice</h2>
      <p>
        For role addresses (<code>info@</code>, <code>billing@</code>,
        <code>support@</code>), our recommendation is to route them
        into the omnichannel / helpdesk app already in your suite
        (Rocket.Chat Omnichannel, Zammad, or an n8n flow). Conversation
        history then lives in that app's database — already covered
        by the suite's restic + Postgres dumps + WORM backup stack.
        If you prefer the email-archive path instead, the role
        mailbox becomes a second account inside one designated user's
        Nextcloud Mail and flows through the same archive path as
        personal mailboxes.
      </p>

      <h2>What we wire up regardless of which one you pick</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>DNS records: <code>MX</code>, <code>SPF</code>, <code>DKIM</code>, <code>DMARC</code>, optional MTA-STS.</li>
        <li>The provider's SMTP credentials wired into the Suite's transactional sender (so password resets and calendar invites send via your provider, not a third party).</li>
        <li>Per-user Nextcloud Mail account, so the team reads / writes mail from the same dashboard as their files, calendar, and tasks.</li>
        <li>Optional personal-mailbox archive into each user's Nextcloud Files (joins the existing restic + Nextcloud versioning + WORM backup).</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="closing">
        Tell us which one you are leaning toward and why; we will
        verify pricing, run a deliverability test, and confirm it
        fits your jurisdictional and language requirements before
        you commit.
      </p>

      <p class="back">
        <a href="/en/guides/">&larr; All guides</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>

  <CTA locale={locale} />
</Base>

<style>
  .guide { padding-bottom: var(--catena-space-16); }
  .guide :global(.container) { max-width: var(--catena-content-wide); }
  .guide h2 { margin-top: var(--catena-space-10); font-size: var(--catena-fs-xl); }
  .guide h3 { margin-top: var(--catena-space-6); font-size: var(--catena-fs-lg); }
  .guide p, .guide li { line-height: var(--catena-lh-relaxed); }
  .guide ul { padding-left: var(--catena-space-6); }
  .guide ul ul { margin-top: var(--catena-space-2); }

  .table-wrap { overflow-x: auto; margin-top: var(--catena-space-4); }
  table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-size: var(--catena-fs-sm);
    min-width: 880px;
  }
  th, td {
    padding: var(--catena-space-3) var(--catena-space-4);
    text-align: left;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--catena-surface-border);
    vertical-align: top;
  }
  thead th {
    font-weight: var(--catena-fw-semibold);
    color: var(--catena-surface-fg-muted);
    font-size: var(--catena-fs-xs);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: var(--catena-tracking-wide);
  }
  tbody th[scope="row"] {
    font-weight: var(--catena-fw-medium);
    color: var(--catena-surface-fg);
    width: 18%;
  }
  .closing {
    margin-top: var(--catena-space-8);
    line-height: var(--catena-lh-relaxed);
    color: var(--catena-surface-fg-muted);
  }
  .back { margin-top: var(--catena-space-8); font-size: var(--catena-fs-sm); }
</style>
